			<p style="font-size:16px;">The flow of control in aÂ <span><b>for</b></span>Â loop is a follows âˆ’</p>

			<ul style="font-size:16px;">
				<li style="background:;">
				<p style="font-size:16px;">If aÂ <span><b>condition</b></span>Â is available, then for loop executes as long as condition is true.</p>
				</li>
				<li style="background:;">
				<p style="font-size:16px;">If aÂ <span><b>for</b></span>Â clause that isÂ <span><b>( init; condition; increment )</b></span>Â is present then âˆ’</p>

				<ul>
					<li style="background:;">
					<p style="font-size:16px;">TheÂ <span><b>init</b></span>Â step is executed first, and only once. This step allows you to declare and initialize any loop control variables. You are not required to put a statement here, as long as a semicolon appears.</p>
					</li>
					<li style="background:;">
					<p style="font-size:16px;">Next, theÂ <span><b>condition</b></span>Â is evaluated. If it is true, the body of the loop is executed. If it is false, the body of the loop does not execute and the flow of control jumps to the next statement just after theÂ <span><b>for</b></span>Â loop.</p>
					</li>
					<li style="background:;">
					<p style="font-size:16px;">After the body of the for loop executes, the flow of control jumps back up to theÂ <span><b>increment</b></span>Â statement. This statement allows you to update any loop control variables. This statement can be left blank, as long as a semicolon appears after the condition.</p>
					</li>
					<li style="background:;">
					<p style="font-size:16px;">The condition is now evaluated again. If it is true, the loop executes and the process repeats itself (body of loop, then increment step, and then again the condition). After the condition becomes false, the for loop terminates.</p>
					</li>
